Experiment Title

Controlling a Stepper Motor Using Arduino and ULN2003 Driver

Components Used

1. Arduino Board

The Arduino is the main microcontroller used to control the stepper motor.
 It executes the program instructions and sends control signals to the motor driver
  to rotate the motor in the desired direction.

2. 28BYJ-48 Stepper Motor

The 28BYJ-48 is a unipolar stepper motor that rotates in small, precise steps.
 It is commonly used in automation and positioning applications where accurate
  movement is required. In this experiment, the motor completes one full revolution
   in both clockwise and anticlockwise directions.

3. ULN2003 Motor Driver Module

The ULN2003 motor driver acts as an interface between the Arduino and the stepper
 motor. Since the Arduino cannot provide sufficient current to drive the motor
  directly, the ULN2003 amplifies the control signals and supplies the required
   current to the motor coils.

4. Stepper Library

The Arduino Stepper library simplifies the control of stepper motors. It provides
 functions for setting motor speed and defining the number of steps the motor should
  rotate.

5. Connecting Wires

Jumper wires are used to establish connections between the Arduino board and the
 ULN2003 driver module.

6. Power Supply

The motor and Arduino are powered through a suitable power source to ensure stable
 operation during motor rotation.

What the Experiment Did

The experiment demonstrated the operation and control of a stepper motor using an
 Arduino and a ULN2003 driver module.

First, the stepper motor was configured with 2048 steps per revolution, meaning
 the motor requires 2048 steps to complete one full rotation. The motor speed was
  set to 10 RPM using the setSpeed() function.

In the program loop:

The motor rotated 2048 steps clockwise, completing one full revolution.
The motor paused for 3 seconds.
The motor then rotated 2048 steps anticlockwise, returning to its original position.
Another 3-second delay was applied before repeating the cycle.

This continuous process allowed observation of motor movement in both directions.

Importance of the Experiment

This experiment is important because it introduces the fundamentals of stepper motor
 control and motion systems.

The experiment helps in understanding:

How stepper motors operate using precise step movements.

The role of motor driver circuits in supplying sufficient current to motors.

Control of rotational direction using programming.

Speed control using the Stepper library.

Applications of stepper motors in automation and robotics.

Stepper motors are extensively used in:

CNC machines
3D printers
Robotic systems
Automated manufacturing equipment
Camera positioning systems
Industrial control systems

The knowledge gained from this experiment forms the foundation for more advanced
 motor control and automation projects.

4. Conclusion

The experiment successfully demonstrated the control of a 28BYJ-48 stepper motor
 using an Arduino and a ULN2003 motor driver. The motor completed one full
  revolution clockwise, paused, and then completed one full revolution
   anticlockwise in a continuous cycle. The activity provided practical experience
    in motor control, direction control, and speed adjustment. Overall, the
     experiment highlighted the importance of stepper motors in applications
      requiring accurate and repeatable positioning, making them essential
       components in modern automation and robotics systems.